The Locust Years of Latin America
The bad news continues to accumulate these days in Latin America.
Economic conditions are deteriorating almost everywhere, social cohesion is unraveling, and political instability is growing.
It is hardly surprising since the majority of Latin American countries have gone nowhere in the past twenty years.
Capital has been sold and national debts have been excessively increased, but nothing lasting and beneficial has been achieved.
These years have truly been devoured by locusts.
Over the past 20 years, the annual growth rate of GDP per capita in Latin America has averaged 0.35%.
At this rate, an economy would take 200 years to double.
In Asia, the standard of living doubles every decade.
With such anemic growth, how can Latin America hope to compete in the global market except through timid wage increases?
The economic stagnation is the responsibility of a bad government, not of bad luck.
If Latin America does not change, it may start to resemble Africa more and more - a region composed of weak states with large informal economies and widespread poverty.
Four factors have put it on this path.
Firstly, in the rush towards privatization, everything, from public services to processing industries, has been put up for sale.
For a brief moment, capital sales helped balance national budgets and also provided resources to support consumption.
Finally, the revenues derived from privatization have produced little within the context of better infrastructure or more competitive exports.
Worse still, the liquidation of state assets was accompanied by massive external borrowing.
In some cases, notably in Argentina, the borrowing undertaken by national buyers exhausted all available credit lines.
Other countries have not fallen to the level of Argentina, but solvency represents a problem in almost every Latin American country.
Secondly, given that the reform did not bring prosperity, the region has become disillusioned.
The inflow of capital produced an effect of wealth, but only as long as they existed.
When the flow of money ceased, wealth dried up.
No sensible politician would commit to another decade of structural reforms that would test the patience of average Latin Americans beyond the limits of electoral survival.
But without a greater number of deep reforms, too few preconditions for economic growth will be in place to attract investments, without which no growth is possible.
This development dilemma announces the third factor: incompetent policies.
The governments that operated along technocratic lines and viewed economic growth as a rising tide that lifts all boats have disappeared.
In Argentina, clumsy presidents succeed one another.
Institutions are being trampled, property rights are being questioned, and an effort of random and even more corrupt redistribution is underway.
Peru and Venezuela have little more chance; Brazil may soon follow the same path.
The popularity of Lula Ignacia da Silva and her team, who conduct opinion polls in the period preceding Brazil's presidential elections, indicates that a large part of the Latin American population is ready to reject traditional governments.
Lula and his party are so far from the dominant economic and political thinking that capital has already begun to flee - even though elections are only in a few months.
In Mexico, democratization has brought greater stability, but this could well turn out to be temporary.
The peso is now excessively overvalued.
If the external balance deteriorates further, the economy risks a hard landing.
Regarding all the good news about the emerging democracy in Mexico, its president is beginning to justify the fears that existed about him: no vision, no Congress, and no team knowing what to do.
The last factor concerns the desperately low savings rate that is endemic to the Americas.
In fact, this is the financial result economically speaking, since where there is little savings, there is little investment - and little basis for accumulating capital and increasing productivity.
Venezuela now longs for the fat years of the OPEC in the 1970s - to which it did not participate, having neglected to develop its oil industry.
The wealth of Argentina is now taking vacation in Miami, perhaps for good.
Brazil and Mexico are perfect examples of countries that have sold their assets and borrowed rather than saved.
The contrast with Asia is striking.
Take China, where savings and investment rates reach almost 40%, where the current account is in surplus and where there is no public debt.
Government institutions are pro-market and the population is well-educated, disciplined, and flexible in learning.
Rewards for risk-taking and initiative are immediate and strongly motivating.
One cannot deny that China remains a poor country.
Its per capita GDP represents only half of that of Brazil.
But with a growth rate in the coastal region of China of about 15% per year, can it seriously be doubted that within the next 15 years, it will surpass Brazil?
In China, despite all the huge problems encountered, things continue to proceed correctly, first due to the massive flow of foreign direct investment and the imminent advantages of joining the WTO.
In Latin America, things continue to fall apart: governments backtrack on reforms and the economy loses ground against the rest of the world.
Latin America was doing well when unregulated funds flowed in, but these times are largely behind us.
We must therefore expect much worse economic, social, and political developments in the years to come.
Demagogues such as Hugo Chavez in Venezuela or Carlos Menem -- an Argentine presidential candidate once again -- may seem like a bad joke, but anyone who cares about the fate of Latin America should not laugh.
